source.Name: Total population
source.Summary: Population: Total population and distribution by age and sex estimated to be consistent with the population by age and sex of the (a) 1950, 1963, 1971, 1995, 2005 censuses; (b) adjusted for under/over count; (c) adjusted for age heaping; (d) adjusted for under enumeration of children under age 15; (e) official estimates through 2023; and with estimates of the subsequent trends in fertility, mortality and international migration.

source.Name: Total fertility rate
source.Summary: Fertility: Total fertility rate and age pattern of fertility based on: (a) registered births classified by age of mother and the underlying female population by age through 2022; (b) birth-histories data from the 1992-1993 ESF-RHS and 1998, 2001 DHS and 1998-1999 LSMS and 2006-2007 RHS-NDHS and 2011-2012 NDHS; (c) births in the household in the preceding 12 (or 24) months classified by age of mother from the 1978 RETRO-EDENIC and 2005 Census; (d) adjusted fertility using Brass P/F ratio method (or variants) with data on children ever born and births in the preceding 12 (or 24/36) months, both classified by age of mother, from the 1978 RETRO-EDENIC; (e) indirect estimates obtained from the application of the reverse survival method to the 1963, 1971 censuses; (f) cohort-completed fertility backdated by the mean age of childbearing from the 1995, 2005 censuses. In addition, the (a) official estimates of age-specific fertility rates through 2006; (b) adjusted fertility using Brass P/F ratio method (or variants) with data on children ever born and births in the preceding 12 (or 24/36) months, both classified by age of mother, from the 1995, 2005 censuses; (c) indirect estimates obtained from the application of the reverse survival method to the 1950, 1995, 2005 censuses and 1955-2003 Education Stats and 2001 LSMS; (d) cohort-completed fertility backdated by the mean age of childbearing from the 1971 Census and 1998, 2001 DHS have been considered.

source.Name: Life expectancy at birth
source.Summary: Overall Mortality: Life expectancy at birth and age pattern of mortality based on: (a) official estimates through 2010; (b) registered deaths by age and sex available through 2022; (c) adjusted for underreporting of infant and child deaths; (d) adult deaths adjusted for underregistration using death distribution methods; (e) mortality rates for older ages were adjusted; (f) estimates using CD West model life tables and estimates of under-five mortality (5q0), and adult mortality (45q15).

source.Name: Age Mortality
source.Summary: Adult and Old Age Mortality: Estimates derived from: (a) deaths by age and sex available from Register through 2022; (b) adjusted for underregistration; (c) recent household deaths data by age and sex from the 2001 DHS; (d) recent household deaths adjusted at adult ages for underregistration using death distribution methods; (e) siblings deaths from the 1992-1993 ESF-RHS; (f) intercensal survivorship from successive census age distributions; (g) International estimates used up to 2021; (h) estimates of under-five, adult and old age mortality. In addition, the (a) recent household deaths data by age and sex from the 1995, 2005 censuses and 2001 LSMS; (b) maternal orphanhood from the 2001 DHS have been considered.

source.Name: Infant/child mortality
source.Summary: Child Mortality: Under-five mortality based on: (a) official estimates of infant and child mortality through 2017; (b) registered infant and child deaths through 2023; (c) direct estimates from births and deaths under-five calculated from full birth histories data from the 1992-1993 ESF-RHS and 1998, 2001 DHS and 2006-2007 RHS-NDHS and 2011-2012 NDHS; (d) indirect estimates from data on children ever born and surviving from the 1971, 1995, 2005 censuses and 1978 RETRO-EDENIC and 1985-1986 ESD; (e) International estimates used up to 2021. In addition, the recent household deaths from the 1995, 2005 censuses and 2001 DHS and 2001 LSMS have been considered.

source.Name: International migration
source.Summary: Migration: International migration based on: (a) information on foreign-born populations from censuses and registers from major countries of destination (Latin American countries, Spain and United States of America); (b) estimates derived as the differences between overall population growth and natural increase; (c) UNHCR statistics on the number of refugees in the main countries of asylum.
